    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1976-02-16T10:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1976-02-16T09:35:00-05:00" n="262"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d262">
                <head>262. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d262fn1"
                        >Source: Ford Library, National Security Adviser, Memoranda of
                        Conversations, 1973–1977, Box 17. Secret; <gloss target="#t_Nodis_1"
                            >Nodis</gloss>. The meeting was held in the Oval Office.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1976-02-16T09:35:00-05:00" to="1976-02-16T10:10:00-05:00"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date">February 16, 1976, 9:35–10:10
                            a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>President <persName corresp="#p_FGR_1">Ford</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Dr. <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>, Secretary
                        of State</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SB_1">Brent Scowcroft</persName>, Assistant to the
                        President for National Security Affairs</item>
                </list>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: My own view is that if this
                    fails, we should suspend <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> until after the
                    elections. This option is so much worse than Option II, but you can’t even get
                    an honest discussion of the issues. Under IV, <gloss target="#t_DOD_1"
                        >DOD</gloss> was willing to give them 230 Backfire. They are not planning
                    more than 450–500, they couldn’t be. And with reductions, the Backfire would be
                    wholly offset. If the Soviets buy this, it will be in terms of <pb facs="1032"
                        n="1001" xml:id="pg_1001"/> Backfire and cruise missile running free and no
                    reductions. I am lukewarm in support of Option II, but I am not bleeding for
                    it.</p>
                <p>President: <persName corresp="#p_RD_2">Rumsfeld</persName>, Brown and those
                    people don’t understand. I agree with you.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: The smart way would have been
                    to pick up their points and build on them. If <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1"
                        >Reagan</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_JHM_1">Jackson</persName> get
                    knocked out, the Soviets will be tougher.</p>
                <p>President: I was so irritated last night that I was ready to junk the whole
                        thing.<note n="2" xml:id="d262fn2">The President met with <persName
                            corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_RD_2"
                            >Rumsfeld</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_CRB_1">Cheney</persName>,
                        and <persName corresp="#p_SB_1">Scowcroft</persName> from 6:06 to 8:05 p.m.
                        on February 15 to discuss <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss>. A very
                        brief memorandum of conversation is ibid. <persName corresp="#p_RD_2"
                            >Rumsfeld</persName>’s record of the meeting is in the digital <persName
                            corresp="#p_RD_2">Donald Rumsfeld</persName> Papers.</note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: The cynicism of these people
                    is sickening.</p>
                <p>President: How do you reconcile the <gloss target="#t_DOD_1">DOD</gloss> attitude
                    with their screaming about the Soviets going all-out on Defense production? I
                    think under the circumstances we have to go with this option. I am not
                    optimistic but I think to go through the trauma it would take for Option II . .
                    .</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: No, you can’t do it. It is
                    just that we must recognize that it isn’t the best thing to do.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion of Latin America, Law of the Sea, and China.]</p>
            </div>
